    "summary": "Yes — standard sinological practice, handles 现象仁 well, mark voice transitions",
    "content": "\n**Yes, this is the right approach.** It is standard practice in English-language sinological philosophy (Graham, Ziporyn, Van Norden all do variants of this). Two brief notes:\n\n**One concern: the 现象仁/现象义/现象礼 compounds.** The author coins these terms by prefixing 现象 (phenomenal) to classical terms. The reader needs to see that \"phenomenal humaneness\" is the author's coinage built on \"humaneness\" (仁), which was just introduced via the classical quotation. The three-step format handles this naturally: step 1 gives the Laozi quote with 仁, step 2 glosses \"humaneness (仁, ren),\" and then the author's 现象仁 becomes \"phenomenal humaneness\" -- the construction is visible. This is important because the entire argument of 后形而上学 depends on the reader seeing that the author is systematically prefixing \"phenomenal\" to classical terms to distinguish experience-level from concept-level. The format makes this move transparent.\n\n**One addition: mark the transition clearly.** When the author shifts from quoting 文言 to analyzing it in modern Chinese, the English should make this transition visible. The 文言 quotes are another voice (Laozi, the Yijing); the analysis is the author's voice. If both are rendered in the same English register, the reader loses track of who is speaking. The original Chinese text (step 1) already serves as a visual marker of the classical voice. Just ensure the English translation of the 文言 (step 2) reads slightly more formal/archaic than the author's own analytical prose that follows.\n"
  }
}
